AGI -&nbsp;A 12-year-old child died> and two other minors were seriously injured in a school shooting in Finland. The police reported it, adding that another child was arrested, even he 12 years ago. The shooting, according to the press from the parents of some pupils, took place in a classroom of a school in Vantaa, north of the capital Helsinki.&nbsp;>
&nbsp;
The police invited local residents to stay at home. The author of the gesture had escaped after the shooting, but was arrested on the other side of a river that wet Vantaa,&nbsp; the fourth largest city in Finland, about 240.000 inhabitants.&nbsp; The child still had the weapon used.&nbsp; The Prime Minister, Petteri Orpo spoke of "unwilling" events. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
The Viertola school in Vantaa, Finland's fourth largest city, has about 800 pupils and 90 employees. They're dating kids between seven and fifteen. "Every person involved in the shooting is underage," the police confirmed.<br> The parents of the pupils told that the shooting took place in a courtroom. A witness told the newspaper Iltalehti that the shots were also echoed in the school's courtyard: "At first, I didn't know it was a weapon. Then he felt a terrible scream and the children crossed the courtyard." The police added that the kid author of the gunshots at first ran away but was stopped shortly after in "quiet mode" on the other side of the river. Iltalehti posted a video shot by a passing car showing two police officers blocking a teenager on the edge of a street in a residential area. For hours the police kept everyone away from the school, inviting people to stay at home.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Then, around noon local time, he brought in the parents waiting outside the school to recover their children. Prime Minister Petteri Orpo said "profoundly shocked". The day began in a "slightening" way, said Interior Minister Mari Rantanen, in a post on X. "I can only imagine the pain and concern that many families are experiencing right now." The police did not provide details on the conditions of the wounded, but announced a press conference in the afternoon.
&nbsp;
Finland was the scene of two gruesome shootings in schools in the early 2000s: in November 2007, a 18-year-old boy opened fire in a secondary school in Jokela, about 50 kilometers north of Helsinki, killing the principal and the nurse along with six pupils, before committing suicide. The following year, in September 2008, there was a shooting at a professional school in Kauhajoki, performed by 22-year-old Matti Juhani Saari, who caused 11 victims. Since then, hundreds of schools have received threats of shooting, as documented by an article published in the Journal of Scandinavian Studies in Criminology and Crime Prevention: the article indicated mental health problems as the main reason for the phenomenon.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
