AGI -&nbsp;Australia may soon experience periods of mega-siccity that will last for more than 20 years. These are the results of a new study by Australian National University (ANU) and the ARC Center of Excellence for Climate Extremes. The shocking discoveries of researchers take into account the human impact on climate > starting from the Industrial Revolution. The team led by the ANU also discovered that the drought periods of the 20th century in southwestern and eastern Australia, including the Murray-Darling basin, were on average longer than the preindustrial period. According to scientists, the results paint a worrying picture of future droughts in Australia, which will be much worse than any other recent experience. Mega-siccity is exceptionally serious, lasting and widespread. It can last decades or even centuries. An example of this is mega-siccity in the southwestern region of the United States, which began in 2000 and continued for more than two decades. The main co-author, Dr. Georgy Falster, of the ANU Research School of Earth Sciences, said that if today in Australia a mega drought occurred, the consequences would be even worse because of climate change, since any drought would occur in a warmer climate context.
&nbsp;
"The combination of climate change and great natural droughts that could last for 20 years means that in the future Australia could experience worse drought than any other recent historical experience," said Dr. Falster.
&nbsp;
"We must consider, and prepare ourselves, the possibility that one of these multi-year mega-siccity may occur in the near future. "One of the problems related to the understanding of prolonged drought in Australia is that our climate observations since 1900 provide us only a handful of examples to work on. This is not representative of the worst scenarios that are only possible through natural climate variations.
&nbsp;
"Thinking when we might expect to see a drought lasting 20 years in the Murray-Darling basin, in Southeast Australia, this varies a lot. We could see a mega-siccity occurring every 150 or 1,000 years.
&nbsp;
"In this study, we paid special attention to the Murray-Darling basin. As Australia's largest agricultural region, it is important to know how severe drought periods in this region could be." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp; The team led by the ANU examined the entire spectrum of drought periods that Australia could experience, including duration and intensity, even without the effects of climate change. They also wanted to find out how the climate change caused by man is now altering the characteristics of the Australian drought. Researchers used different climate models to simulate drought periods during the last millennium - from the year 850 to the year 2000 - to determine how they could change in the future. This includes predicting how long the Australian drought could last and how much it might be dry.
&nbsp;
"One of the most contrasting results of our work is that it is possible that drought in Australia lasts much longer than any other drought we have experienced in recent times. We should expect the drought to occur for 20 years or more," said Dr Falster. "Mega-siccity is part of the natural variations of the Australian climate. But, what a worrying thing, we are now adding to the mix the climate changes caused by man, and this is probably increasing the possibilities of the next mega-secure here.
&nbsp;
"We compared the simulated droughts in the 20th century, from 1900 to 2000, with those of the preindustrial period, before 1850, to see if the climate change caused by man influenced the way in which the Australians live today drought". Professor Nerilie Abram, co-author of the study, also of ANU, said that climate change caused by man is contributing to longer drought periods in Southwestern and eastern Australia, including the Murray-Darling basin. These are also the regions where we can expect a future fall in rainfall due to climate change, thus increasing the risk of drought.
&nbsp;
"It is likely that changes in drought intensity may still occur while climate change continues to deteriorate," said Professor Abram. "An example of this is the 21st century 'Tinderbox Drought', which lasted only three years but was exceptionally intense and created conditions for the forest fires of the Black Summer. Tinderbox's drought was probably made more severe by climate change.
&nbsp;
"The only thing we can do to reduce the potential gravity and duration of future drought is to quickly reduce greenhouse gas emissions. For example, quickly switching to renewable energy sources. "We can also reduce the impacts of future drought by preparing us with water storage and management plans and community support networks." The research is published in a special edition of the magazine Hydrology and Earth System Sciences . This work was co-directed by ANU and the University of Sydney in collaboration with the University of New South Wales (UNSW), the University of Wollongong and the University of Monash.

