AGI - Former President Donald Trump deposited the $175 million bond as a payment guarantee of over 450> million which he was convicted by the Manhattan court for a tax and financial fraud case > . The American media report it. Trump presented a "bond" issued by the Knight Specialty Insurance Company. Last week, judges from the New York appeal division reduced from 464 to 175 million the amount to be deposited pending the appeal. tycoon had been granted ten more days.
&nbsp;
Trump thus avoided the foreclosure of goods, > a concrete hypothesis after condemnation. Trump, convicted of illegally inflating the value of assets > of his assets for years to have bank loans on advantageous terms, > he should pay more than 460 million dollars, which amounts to the sum of 350 million dollars required by the State, to which more than one hundred million interests have been accrued in these years. At first the tycoon would have to pay the whole figure by March 25, but the judges of the state appeal court recognized him last week a strong discount, forcing him to pay 175 million, and giving him another ten days of time.
&nbsp;
Trump has respected the commitment with a few days ahead. The instrument used is the 'bond', a financial guarantee other than >sia fidejussion for both purposes and characteristics. Fidejussion is, basically, a contract in which an insurance company or a bank undertakes to ensure the fulfillment of a third person's obligation. This guarantee is generally used in contexts such as contracts, as a guarantee of the solvency of the contractor. The bond used by Trump is required, instead, in the American judicial system and concerns legal appeals in the United States.
&nbsp;
When a party loses a cause and decides to appeal, it is required to provide an 'appeal bond': this bond, made available by a financial company, is used to ensure that, if the appellant will lose again in the classroom, it will in any case be able to cover the costs and damages that the other party has suffered. In this case the State of New York. The cost goes from three to ten percent of the figure. According to American media reports, tycoon should pay to the company that issued the bond, the Knight Speciality Insurance Company, a minimum percentage of three hundred, equal to a little more than five million dollars, but that can also exceed ten million.
&nbsp;
Money that will be paid even in case the former president loses the appeal. But without the company's intervention, Trump should have paid with money taken from his current accounts. According to what the New York Times reported last month, tycoon has a wealth of over six billion dollars, but few hundred million liquidity.

